   "source": [
    "List Comprehension - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "42e59250-ad91-4d28-b439-47b1e742e2e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Quick Recap\n",
    "\n",
    "You should already know what list comprehensions are\n",
    "\n",
    "goal -> generate a list by transforming and optionally filtering another iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "- start with some iterable (other_list = ['this', 'is', 'a', 'parrot']\n",
    "- create empty new list (new_list = [])\n",
    "- iterate over original iterable (for item in other_list:)\n",
    "- skip over certain values; filter (if len(item) > 2:)\n",
    "- transform value and append to new list (new_list.append(item[::-1]))\n",
    "\n",
    "List Comprehension\n",
    "new_list = [item[::-1] for item in other_list if len(item) > 2] <- list comprehensioon due to square bracket\n",
    "         transformation iteration          filter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "aeacd654-af84-46ab-84a4-8019b6dcead1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Formatting the Comprehension Expression\n",
    "\n",
    "If comprehension expression gets too long it can be split over multiple lines\n",
    "Ex/ Create a list of squares of all integers between 1 and 100 that are not divisible by 2, 3, or 5\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = [i**2 for i in range(1, 101) if i%2 and i%3 and i%5]\n",
    "\n",
    "We could write over multiple lines\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = [i**2\n",
    "      for i in range(1, 101)\n",
    "      if i%2 and i%3 and i%5]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "04fef6d7-5c40-4be3-afc7-0790ee4093a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Comprehension Internals\n",
    "\n",
    "Comprehensions have their own local scope - just like a function\n",
    "We should think of list comprehension as being wrapped in a function that is created by Python that will return new list when executed\n",
    "\n",
    "sq = [i**2 for i in range(10)]\n",
    "              RHS\n",
    "\n",
    "when RHS is compiled: Python creates a temporary function that will be used to evaluate the comprehension\n",
    "\n",
    "def temp():\n",
    "    new_list = []\n",
    "    for i in range(10):\n",
    "        new_list.append(i**2)\n",
    "    return new_list\n",
    "\n",
    "When the line is executed:\n",
    "Executes temp()\n",
    "Stores the returned object (list) in memory\n",
    "Points sq to that object\n",
    "\n",
    "We will dissassemble some Python code"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "11bbf63d-ea81-476e-a471-9dd5c5eaa5d8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Comprehension Scopes\n",
    "\n",
    "So comprehensions are basically functions\n",
    "They have their own local scope\n",
    "\n",
    "[item ** 2 for item in range(100)] <- item is local symbol\n",
    "\n",
    "But they can access global variables:\n",
    "\n",
    "# module1.py\n",
    "num = 100\n",
    "sq = [item**2 for item in range(num)]\n",
    "\n",
    "item is local, num is global\n",
    "\n",
    "As well as nonlocal variables\n",
    "\n",
    "def my_func(num):\n",
    "    sq = [item**2 for item in range(num)]\n",
    "\n",
    "num is non-local symbol; closure"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "62d7d8ed-4601-42a7-bf8e-7d7bb089c5c6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Nested Comprehensions\n",
    "\n",
    "Comprehensions can be nested within each other\n",
    "And since they are functions, a nested comprehension can access (nonlocal) variables form the enclosing comprehension\n",
    "\n",
    "------------------------------------------- outer comprehension (local i)\n",
    "[[i*j for j in range(5)] for i in range(5)] \n",
    "  --------------------- nested comprehension (closure; local j, free variable i)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "b3388687-6079-4e9b-8128-0597fb44c261",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Nested Loops in Comprehensions\n",
    "\n",
    "We can have nested loops (as many levels) in comprehensions\n",
    "Not the same as nested comprehensions\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(5):\n",
    "    for j in range(5):\n",
    "        for k in range(5):\n",
    "            l.append((i, j, k))\n",
    "\n",
    "l = [(i, j, k) for i in range(5) for j in range(5) for k in range(5)]\n",
    "\n",
    "Nested loops in comprehensions can also contain if statements\n",
    "The order of for and if statements does matter, ust like normal set of for loops and if statements\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(5):\n",
    "    for j in range(5):\n",
    "        if i==j:\n",
    "            l.append((i, j))\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(5):\n",
    "    if i==j:\n",
    "        for j in range(5):\n",
    "            l.append((i, j))\n",
    "WONT WORK j NOT DEFINED\n",
    "\n",
    "l = [(i, j) for i in range(5) for j in range(5) if i == j] WORKS\n",
    "l = [(i, j) for i in range(5) if i == j for j in range(5)] WONT WORK, j DEFINED BEFORE"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8cb6d607-993b-40b5-9480-0bb5106000a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Nested Loops in Comprehensions\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(1, 6):\n",
    "    if i%2 == 0:\n",
    "        for j in range(1, 6):\n",
    "            if j%3 == 0:\n",
    "                l.append((i, j))\n",
    "\n",
    "[(i,j)\n",
    " for i in range(1,6) if i%2==0\n",
    " for j in range(1,6) if j%3==0]\n",
    "\n",
    "---------------------------------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(1, 6):\n",
    "    for j in range(1, 6):\n",
    "        if i%2 == 0:\n",
    "            if j%3 == 0:\n",
    "                l.append((i, j))\n",
    "\n",
    "[(i,j)\n",
    " for i in range(1,6)\n",
    " for j in range(1,6)\n",
    " if i%2==0\n",
    " if j%3==0]\n",
    "\n",
    "---------------------------------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "l = []\n",
    "for i in range(1, 6):\n",
    "    for j in range(1, 6):\n",
    "        if i%2 == 0 and j%3 == 0:\n",
    "            l.append((i, j))\n",
    "\n",
    "[(i,j)\n",
    " for i in range(1,6)\n",
    " for j in range(1,6)\n",
    " if i%2==0 and j%3==0]"
   ]
  },
